          "title": "Jeremiah 25 in canonical perspective",
          "body": "This chapter exercises wide canonical influence. Daniel 9:2 explicitly cites 'the word of the LORD to Jeremiah the prophet' — almost certainly Jeremiah 25:11-12 — as the textual basis for Daniel's great penitential prayer in Babylon. Daniel, reading the seventy-year oracle in Babylonian captivity, understands that the period is nearing completion and intercedes accordingly. The cup-of-wrath imagery flows forward into Habakkuk 2:16, Lamentations 4:21, Ezekiel 23:31-34, and ultimately into the New Testament's eschatological imagery (Revelation 14:10; 16:19; 18:6), where Babylon again receives the cup and the Lamb administers the wrath of God to all who worship the beast. The universal judgment catalog of 25:18-26 anticipates Ezekiel's oracles against the nations (Ezekiel 25-32) and Isaiah's 'Little Apocalypse' (Isaiah 24-27). Jeremiah 25 is not a self-contained historical curiosity; it is the prophetic foundation for the canonical theme that Yahweh's sovereignty is not tribal but universal, and that His patience — however long — has a historically verifiable terminus."
